{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616533"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16405"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16405"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.24,0.04,0.08,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74857"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9096"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60363"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7146"},{"type":"tags","id":"10358"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21605"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74857"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is studying the neural basis of skill acquisition in sports. They are particularly interested in understanding which part of the brain is responsible for learning and perfecting complex movement patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following brain structures plays the most essential role in acquiring and refining motor skills?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebellum","Basal ganglia","Hippocampus","Amygdala","Prefrontal cortex"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E serves as the primary neural centre for acquiring and refining motor skills. It functions as an error-detection system by continuously comparing intended movements with executed movements. Through this process, it helps develop and store motor programs that enable smooth, coordinated actions. Individuals with cerebellar damage typically demonstrate impaired motor learning, poor balance, and uncoordinated movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlternative structures have different primary functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal ganglia\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to movement regulation and habit formation, but primarily focus on action selection and movement initiation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehippocampus\u003C/strong\u003E specialises in forming explicit memories and spatial maps, rather than motor skill acquisition\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eamygdala\u003C/strong\u003E processes emotional responses and emotional memory formation, having minimal involvement in motor learning\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprefrontal cortex\u003C/strong\u003E manages executive functions and complex planning, but does not directly control motor skill acquisition\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum\u0027s unique ability to process both sensory feedback and motor commands makes it essential for learning and perfecting physical skills, from simple movements to complex athletic manoeuvres.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The cerebellum integrates sensory and motor information to enable smooth, coordinated movements and motor skill acquisition.","Damage to the cerebellum results in impaired motor learning, ataxia, and difficulties with balance and coordination.","Motor learning requires continuous feedback between intended and executed movements to refine motor programs."],"references":["De Zeeuw CI, Ten Brinke MM. Motor Learning and the Cerebellum. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2015 Sep 1;7(9):a021683. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a021683. PMID: 26330521; PMCID: PMC4563713.","Raslau FD, Klein AP, Ulmer JL, Mathews V, Mark LP. Memory part 1: overview. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2014 Nov-Dec;35(11):2058-60. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A4059. Epub 2014 Jul 17. PMID: 25034776; PMCID: PMC7965175","Jawabri KH, Cascella M. Physiology, Explicit Memory. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554551/","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60363"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16405"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60363"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T23:15:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T23:16:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9096"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74857"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoj